@thomasvalette Ah, the problem is indeed the win+l hotkey. Thanks a lot for this information.

Once the screen is locked, 'keyboard' stops receiving events (Windows security feature to avoid keyloggers from stealing your windows password). If your screen locks quick enough and you hold the hotkey long enough, the key up events are not received. Hotkeys stop working because the library thinks the windows key is still held.

This is a tricky one, but identifying the bug is half the battle.

On 64-bit NetBSD, the following example code will identify 32-bit
processes:

````
#include <string.h>
#include <errno.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <kvm.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
	int pid, res;
	struct kinfo_proc2 *kp;
	if (argc != 2) {
		printf("usage: %s pid\n", argv[0]);
		exit(1);
	}
	kvm_t *kvmp = kvm_open(NULL, NULL, NULL, KVM_NO_FILES, NULL);
	if (kvmp == NULL) {
		printf("kvm_open failed: %s\n", strerror(errno));
		exit(1);
	}
	pid = atoi(argv[1]);
	kp = kvm_getproc2(kvmp, KERN_PROC_PID, pid, sizeof(*kp), &res);
	if (res != 1) {
		printf("kvm_getproc2 failed: %s\n", strerror(errno));
		exit(1);
	}
	if (kp->p_flag & P_32)
		printf("it is a 32bit process\n");
	else
		printf("not a 32bit process\n");
	kvm_close(kvmp);
}
````

On 32-bit NetBSD the flag will never be set, because all processes are
32-bit.

