@tigran-a If you don't want `consume()` to return `None`, you can try using `consume(block=True)` in combination with `get_balanced_consumer(consumer_timeout_ms=-1)`. This will cause it to block indefinitely until it has a non-`None` message to return.

I'd need some more context to properly diagnose the second issue. The consumer group somehow got into a state where two consumers wanted the same partition at the same time. I imagine this is a bit more likely to happen if you're using a consumer group with a number of participants equal to the number of partitions on your topic, as you say you're doing.

As for the duplicated messages, neither Kafka nor PyKafka make any guarantees about exactly-once delivery in balanced consumer groups, and we've seen in many cases that duplicate message delivery is possible as a result of partition rebalancing. You can check out what @ryan-stateless was doing in [this issue](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/issues/288) to serve a use case that sounds similar to yours.

Ah, that's an off-by-one error on randint. I can confirm that this happens on master, too.

In addition to the off-by-one error, the way that we are generating S&P noise is incorrect. With a probability of 1.0, we say, "generate `image.size` coordinates at random, then replace those with 1s". Of course the problem is that generating that many random coordinates results in repeated coordinates, and we end up replacing ~2/3 of the coordinates at random, on average. For small probabilities this doesn't matter, which is probably why it's gone unnoticed for so long.

