@wbober, gcc6 sets the default mode for C++ to `-std=gnu++14`.  Couple questions:

1. Are you OK with setting the C++ mode to an earlier version?
2. What features of gcc6 interest you - gcc6 is relatively bleeding edge :)

One possible option: introduce a `CoapSocket` object, that serves as the intermediary between a UDP socket (or DTLS session) and one or both of `CoapClient` and `CoapServer`.  `CoapClient` and `CoapServer` would be modified to bind to `CoapSocket` rather than directly to a UDP socket.  The `CoapSocket` would be responsible for sending a CoAP Reset message if neither the Client nor Server instances could handle the CoAP message.

FWIW, it seems that others CoAP implementers have [suffered](https://github.com/mcollina/node-coap/issues/39) from needing to support the CoAP client and server binding to the same port.

